to shout out, that's Hunter Glanz. He's also at Cal Poly. We're both faculty, and he helped

00:00:17.480 --> 00:00:22.080
me with this project, is involved in the, excuse me, the coding and everything. We decided

00:00:22.080 --> 00:00:26.040
not to switch off talking in a short session, but if you have questions, etc., you can ask

00:00:26.040 --> 00:00:31.920
him as well. So right there, making noises. Okay, so in this talk, I kind of just want

00:00:31.920 --> 00:00:38.119
to tell you about what I've done with R in the really, really intro level classes. So

00:00:38.119 --> 00:00:41.520
the way I'm going to structure this, basically there's a lot of window dressing. I want to

00:00:41.520 --> 00:00:46.240
give you some background on what courses we have at Cal Poly, the advantages and challenges

00:00:46.240 --> 00:00:51.320
of using R in some of these classes, which I'm sure many of you are familiar with, and

00:00:51.320 --> 00:00:55.439
then like what my lab assignments look like, what are the students being asked to do, and

00:00:55.560 --> 00:00:59.560
then the reason for the hamburger, apart from it being mid-afternoon and lunch has worn

00:00:59.560 --> 00:01:04.959
off, is that the meat of this talk is these pre-lab exercises that Hunter and I have built

00:01:04.959 --> 00:01:11.440
in Shiny that have kind of helped us introduce R to beginners. And then I don't know, I've

00:01:11.440 --> 00:01:16.360
got some student outcome information. I've surveyed the students, so hopefully you think

00:01:16.360 --> 00:01:21.199
lettuce is also important to hamburgers. Oh, I forgot that I have a clicker. I'm not used

00:01:21.199 --> 00:01:26.320
to this fanciness. And then some take-home messages, advice, if any of you are teaching

00:01:26.320 --> 00:01:32.680
such classes. So at Cal Poly, the courses using R, we do have a dedicated R class, so

00:01:32.680 --> 00:01:37.800
that one you would hope involves R in some way. But we also have a lot of upper level

00:01:37.800 --> 00:01:42.959
classes, and those will involve some coding in order to get the concepts across, et cetera.

00:01:42.959 --> 00:01:49.059
Most of the professors seem to favor R, although it's up to our decision there. But then we

00:01:49.059 --> 00:01:53.540
also have these service level classes, what we call the introductory classes for non-majors.

00:01:53.540 --> 00:01:57.459
And these are the classes where there's no stat or CS background. There's no prerequisites

00:01:57.459 --> 00:02:02.699
of any kind. And so everyone agrees that these students should see software in some way.

00:02:02.699 --> 00:02:07.779
But typically people are using applets. There's some debate over whether we should use R or

00:02:07.779 --> 00:02:12.100
use something, an applet or Jump or Minitab, some of these easier kind of point and click

00:02:12.100 --> 00:02:19.020
approaches. That's debatable. There's no opposition to using R as kind of the tool. But what

00:02:19.020 --> 00:02:23.059
is really kind of unpopular is that students in these classes should code, because these

00:02:23.059 --> 00:02:27.500
are not stat or CS majors. These are, for my class, they're bio majors, viticulture,

00:02:27.500 --> 00:02:31.460
food science, animal science, things like that.

00:02:31.460 --> 00:02:35.860
So this is the class I want to talk about. It's a service level class that I teach. And

00:02:35.860 --> 00:02:40.100
I do think there's a lot of advantages to introducing coding in this class. You may

00:02:40.100 --> 00:02:44.380
or may not agree with me. Pedagogically, I think that thinking through things with code

00:02:44.380 --> 00:02:48.940
forces them to not just memorize steps. What are the steps of a hypothesis test or a t-test

00:02:48.940 --> 00:02:53.740
or same thing, linear regression, et cetera. They have to kind of plan ahead, plan their

00:02:53.740 --> 00:02:57.460
output and not memorize formulas.

00:02:57.460 --> 00:03:03.139
Conceptually, I think we live in an age where data is all digital. So thinking of data as

00:03:03.139 --> 00:03:07.740
a digital object and how do people interact with it, it's a good way to kind of interface

00:03:07.740 --> 00:03:12.339
with how this is being done in the real world and to think of data as information and not

00:03:12.339 --> 00:03:16.500
a list of numbers that's handed to you on an exam.

00:03:16.500 --> 00:03:20.740
And then practically speaking, of course, not all of them are going to be data scientists

00:03:20.740 --> 00:03:26.899
or creators, but they do need to understand how it's done in the real world. I don't know

00:03:26.899 --> 00:03:33.779
why we are still using these T tables here and normal Z tables. Nobody uses that in the

00:03:33.779 --> 00:03:37.860
real world. We're all just going to use P-norm, Q-norm or our language of choice if this were

00:03:37.860 --> 00:03:42.699
not an R conference. It makes no sense to be using things in class that are never, ever,

00:03:42.699 --> 00:03:45.100
ever going to be encountered in the real world.

00:03:45.100 --> 00:03:49.220
So this is my opinion, anyway, that I think these students should benefit from seeing

00:03:49.220 --> 00:03:54.020
code. It's not always easy, though. These are ‑‑ I keep forgetting. We don't have

00:03:54.020 --> 00:03:55.699
these at Cal Poly. It's a state school.

00:03:55.699 --> 00:04:04.940
So some of the challenges that I've encountered with these new students, logistically, I went

00:04:04.940 --> 00:04:08.179
in the first time I used R in this class. I was gung‑ho. I had put so much thought

00:04:08.179 --> 00:04:13.179
into how to make this gentle, you know, and introduce them to coding. And what I instead

00:04:13.179 --> 00:04:18.140
dealt with for the whole class is where's my downloads folder?

00:04:18.140 --> 00:04:22.179
These kids are 17 to 23. I thought they'd grown up with computers and it was natural.

00:04:22.179 --> 00:04:24.779
But I've learned there's kind of a sweet spot in between the people that are frightened

00:04:24.779 --> 00:04:28.700
of computers and the people that are frightened of downloads folders.

00:04:28.700 --> 00:04:33.980
So that was a challenge. There's ways around it. And I don't want to dwell on this too

00:04:33.980 --> 00:04:37.660
much. This is very important to the class, but it's not really my contribution. So there's

00:04:37.660 --> 00:04:41.779
many better people than I to speak of this. But I just want to mention using cloud servers

00:04:41.779 --> 00:04:46.500
has really helped in this class. RStudio Cloud is awesome. Amazon Web Services, you can set

00:04:46.500 --> 00:04:50.019
up your own home cloud, which is what we've done at Cal Poly.

00:04:50.019 --> 00:04:54.980
And then using notebooks, you know, to feed them code, that helps. Or to call your own

00:04:54.980 --> 00:04:58.700
scripts, et cetera. GitHub Classroom is really cool. I've just gotten started with that.

00:04:58.700 --> 00:05:02.059
That's a nice way to just package everything off to these students.

00:05:02.779 --> 00:05:07.739
And then they use this package as kind of idiot proof, as they say. So these things

00:05:07.739 --> 00:05:12.100
can help. I would just point you to those if you're interested in using R for people

00:05:12.100 --> 00:05:15.619
that are frightened of downloads folders.

00:05:15.619 --> 00:05:22.140
But anyway, the other challenges that I run into besides those logistics are pedagogical.

00:05:22.140 --> 00:05:26.220
I want to involve coding in my teaching, but I'm not teaching coding. I'm teaching statistics

00:05:26.220 --> 00:05:30.100
and I'm teaching concepts of statistics. And so how do I do that without ending up just

00:05:30.100 --> 00:05:35.260
teaching coding? And what I get in feedback a lot is we spent all this time learning R

00:05:35.260 --> 00:05:39.260
and it wasn't on the exam. I did put R output that they have to read on the exam, but they

00:05:39.260 --> 00:05:43.100
don't have to write code. There's no coding questions and so forth.

00:05:43.100 --> 00:05:48.859
So this is a big question of kind of how to synthesize those ideas. And then these students

00:05:48.859 --> 00:05:52.140
are mostly students who are forced to take stat, don't want to take stat. They don't

00:05:52.140 --> 00:05:56.140
think they like math. And so it just adds one more thing for them to be scared about

00:05:56.140 --> 00:05:59.579
in this intro class.

00:05:59.579 --> 00:06:06.260
So I did a survey, I did some extensive surveys of my class this fall that ended just in December.

00:06:06.260 --> 00:06:09.459
And this is what the students had to say. I had the question, I feel nervous about my

00:06:09.459 --> 00:06:13.779
ability to complete the lab assignment. And over the first three lab assignments here,

00:06:13.779 --> 00:06:16.420
they're pretty nervous, right? More than half of them are saying that they strongly agree

00:06:16.420 --> 00:06:20.339
or agree that they're nervous about it. And it wasn't really getting better actually across

00:06:20.339 --> 00:06:24.179
the assignments. So this is something they find daunting. And I will readily admit that,

00:06:24.179 --> 00:06:28.299
that it's a challenge for them.

00:06:28.299 --> 00:06:31.239
So let me tell you what these assignments are that are so terrifying that I'm using

00:06:31.239 --> 00:06:36.260
in my class. When I first started out, okay, so here's an example of a data set that I

00:06:36.260 --> 00:06:39.739
use. I'm sure many of you have seen it. It's the wine data set. We've got a whole bunch

00:06:39.739 --> 00:06:44.140
of chemical measures of wine. And then we've got this measure at the bottom, quality, that's

00:06:44.140 --> 00:06:49.940
going to say if it's a good or a bad wine as rated by experts. So the idea is what different

00:06:49.940 --> 00:06:54.420
chemical properties does the wine have to be a good wine?

00:06:54.420 --> 00:06:57.619
And so in my first version of these labs, and these are just snippets from the labs.

00:06:57.619 --> 00:07:03.420
They're obviously much longer and formatted differently. But I just give them this t-test

00:07:03.420 --> 00:07:08.339
code and I ask them questions about it. And their job is to look at that output and interpret

00:07:08.339 --> 00:07:13.820
it correctly. So it's not really coding, right? It's reading output, but it's not coding.

00:07:13.820 --> 00:07:19.579
And then the next version was kind of reproduce my process. So first I would do the same thing,

00:07:19.579 --> 00:07:22.940
ask them something, give them that code. And then I'd say, well, here what I asked them

00:07:22.940 --> 00:07:27.380
about was pH level. Does the pH level of the wine matter to the quality? And then I said,

00:07:27.420 --> 00:07:31.299
well, now suppose I've made some claim about density. Can you back that claim up? And all

00:07:31.299 --> 00:07:35.380
they're going to do is copy, paste, and write density where pH is. Or ideally that's what

00:07:35.380 --> 00:07:38.899
they're going to do. You'd be surprised the number of different things they would do,

00:07:38.899 --> 00:07:43.899
such as writing t.test.density, weird stuff like that, because they're so new to this.

00:07:43.899 --> 00:07:47.179
I have a clicker.

00:07:47.179 --> 00:07:51.700
Version three is where I really think my students are being statisticians. This is where I have

00:07:51.700 --> 00:07:56.660
not given them almost anything. I have said, choose three chemical attributes of the wine,

00:07:56.660 --> 00:08:00.820
make me some plots, do some t-tests. This is what their lab assignment literally looked

00:08:00.820 --> 00:08:04.820
like on this, and this is the third lab assignment. So this is week four. I don't do one the first

00:08:04.820 --> 00:08:11.100
week of a 10-week course. So this is cool, right? I think it's really cool that non-majors

00:08:11.100 --> 00:08:16.179
can handle this, and they really can. But how do I get them there is the question, without

00:08:16.179 --> 00:08:20.100
having given them anything right here to work with.

00:08:20.100 --> 00:08:26.420
So what we came up with, this kind of intermediate transition tool, is these pre-lab exercises

00:08:26.420 --> 00:08:32.780
in Shiny. And so where this idea came from was at ICOTS, the conference on teaching statistics

00:08:32.780 --> 00:08:37.219
in Japan last summer. Hunter and I went to two talks. I think there's a rule that you

00:08:37.219 --> 00:08:40.820
have to quote Hadley if you're going to talk at this conference. That's what I heard. But

00:08:40.820 --> 00:08:43.739
really, there were these two talks back to back that really influenced us. The main one

00:08:43.739 --> 00:08:48.580
was Amelia McNamara saying we need a bridge between there's learning statistics, those

00:08:48.580 --> 00:08:53.900
are applets, and there's doing statistics, that's being a true programmer or coder, and

00:08:54.260 --> 00:08:57.580
there's not really a bridge in between these things right now. And this kind of matched

00:08:57.580 --> 00:09:02.340
a vision that I've had for a long time floating in my brain. And then Hadley backing up that

00:09:02.340 --> 00:09:06.659
not all statisticians need to be coders, but if you're not interacting with code, are you

00:09:06.659 --> 00:09:11.739
really doing statistics? I think the challenges and the advantages pedagogically, they all

00:09:11.739 --> 00:09:15.619
pale in comparison to the fact that if we're offering to teach statistics and we don't

00:09:15.619 --> 00:09:19.859
teach them to think about it as a digital process, we are not teaching them statistics.

00:09:20.859 --> 00:09:27.340
I'm sure many will disagree, but I would love to argue with you. So that's the idea. So

00:09:27.340 --> 00:09:30.979
that's where this came from. So Hunter and I, we went upstairs at this conference and

00:09:30.979 --> 00:09:34.780
we sat down amongst all the Japanese business people having lunch and we coded for a couple

00:09:34.780 --> 00:09:40.340
hours and then spent the whole summer continuing to develop these things. So the idea is the

00:09:40.340 --> 00:09:46.020
principles behind these tools, we figured they should kind of have immediate results,

00:09:46.020 --> 00:09:50.900
right? What's nice about applets is the students go very quickly to seeing output that is exciting

00:09:50.900 --> 00:09:57.940
and interpretable. So we wanted to maintain that to kind of immediately see the process.

00:09:57.940 --> 00:10:01.640
But then we wanted to require them to be generating the queries, to not be selecting from a drop

00:10:01.640 --> 00:10:08.140
down menu or clicking a checkbox or so forth as a real coder would. And we also wanted

00:10:08.140 --> 00:10:11.299
to make really clear what's kind of built into R versus what they're choosing because

00:10:11.299 --> 00:10:15.460
this is not an R specific, I'm not trying to teach them R. So I want them to be able

00:10:15.460 --> 00:10:19.299
to interact then with another language and understand we have to think about what variables

00:10:19.299 --> 00:10:25.020
we're using, even if the function to make a box plot or whatever has a different name.

00:10:25.020 --> 00:10:29.039
And then I really wanted to link the concepts and questions from lecture, the big ideas,

00:10:29.039 --> 00:10:37.739
to what was happening with the code. So I want to do a demo here. And I've got a backup

00:10:37.739 --> 00:10:42.099
plan but I think these are working fine on shinyapps.io. So I'll have these links at

00:10:42.099 --> 00:10:46.340
the end. I've got three of these hosted on shinyapps.io if you want to demo them. For

00:10:46.340 --> 00:10:50.619
the class we hosted them separately because shinyapps would get pummeled and I would not

00:10:50.619 --> 00:10:53.979
be able to handle it on my free account. But these ones are here if you guys want to try

00:10:53.979 --> 00:10:59.940
them. So the idea here is this was their first lab exercise. It's built on learn R. So someone

00:10:59.940 --> 00:11:06.500
asked a question earlier. A really nice package for this kind of thing. And the key here is

00:11:06.500 --> 00:11:12.859
that what we're going to do is we have the Titanic data set for all of these exercises.

00:11:12.859 --> 00:11:17.299
And they have to choose the variables. So let's say we want to look at gender and then

00:11:17.299 --> 00:11:25.260
we want to see who survived. And so what this does and kind of the key point is it fills

00:11:25.260 --> 00:11:34.580
in that code line there. So that line of code, they're seeing the blue is the thing that

00:11:34.580 --> 00:11:38.099
is, you know, a name that was chosen, but I chose it. They didn't just input it just

00:11:38.099 --> 00:11:41.940
now. And the red is the stuff that they just selected. And the rest of it is just the syntax

00:11:41.940 --> 00:11:48.539
of this particular coding language. And so then we see, okay, they used facet grid. And

00:11:48.539 --> 00:11:52.260
that's you can kind of get an idea of what's going on, but not so great. So we can go down

00:11:52.260 --> 00:11:56.859
to stack bar charts, things like that. Make different choices. They can see the output

00:11:56.859 --> 00:12:00.020
immediately and decide which of those plots answers their question better. Which one is

00:12:00.020 --> 00:12:05.979
going to show you that men tended to die and women tended to survive on the Titanic.

00:12:05.979 --> 00:12:12.940
And so additionally, we have this idea of tying it to the concepts in class. So here's

00:12:12.940 --> 00:12:17.900
the exercise for t-tests where we can say, all right, I'd like to make claims about the

00:12:17.900 --> 00:12:23.859
age on Titanic. The age of the passengers. And under the null, let's say 30. And let's

00:12:23.859 --> 00:12:30.099
say we're interested in testing whether the average age was less than 30 for some reason.

00:12:30.099 --> 00:12:34.460
And so we can see this in words that they've been seeing in class. The hypothesis is that

00:12:34.460 --> 00:12:38.580
the true mean is equal to 30 versus less than 30. We can see this in code, again, with the

00:12:38.580 --> 00:12:42.940
blue and red. And then we can see the output that they have to interpret. And LearnR is

00:12:42.940 --> 00:12:47.380
nice. It's got a good interface for including some questions. We can say, oh, look, what

00:12:47.380 --> 00:12:54.739
sample mean did I observe? Well, that was 29.547. There we go. And it will tell them

00:12:54.739 --> 00:12:58.260
right away they got it right. So they're able to kind of check and make sure that they've

00:12:58.260 --> 00:13:05.020
gotten the output that was expected. And then the last one I want to show you, just to tie

00:13:05.020 --> 00:13:11.140
all these principles together, is the normal random variables in general. So we could say

00:13:11.140 --> 00:13:15.900
something like, let's say we have a normal random variable with a mean of 67 and a standard

00:13:15.900 --> 00:13:21.140
deviation of 3. And I'm interested in the area below 60. So again, I'm tying this to

00:13:21.140 --> 00:13:25.140
the way they've seen it in class, which is sort of this notation of normally distributed

00:13:25.140 --> 00:13:29.619
and what's the probability. And then we can see the code, the result. And then I made

00:13:29.619 --> 00:13:32.700
these little illustrations just so they can see what's going on, what the picture looks

00:13:32.700 --> 00:13:36.099
like there. So all these things that they see typically in lecture all in one place

00:13:36.099 --> 00:13:42.140
and kind of being dynamically generated thanks to the magic of Shiny and the coding that

00:13:42.140 --> 00:13:45.219
Hunter and I have done, I suppose.

00:13:45.219 --> 00:13:52.380
So those are the exercises. There we go. And so let me tell you what happened when I finally

00:13:52.380 --> 00:13:56.340
used these. So I started these out on my summer class with only 18 students and used them

00:13:56.340 --> 00:14:03.059
with 108 students this fall. The first thing is students definitely recognize that R is

00:14:03.059 --> 00:14:07.859
applicable. This question is, as the in-class lab activity helped me understand how statistical

00:14:07.859 --> 00:14:11.820
analyses are conducted in the real world, they overwhelmingly agree or at least feel

00:14:11.820 --> 00:14:16.539
neutrally about that. No one is arguing with that.

00:14:16.539 --> 00:14:21.140
They recognize the value to themselves. This one says the in-class activities helped me

00:14:21.140 --> 00:14:26.260
understand the concepts from the week's material. And you can see they kind of over time started

00:14:26.260 --> 00:14:29.179
to see more how this was helping them. I don't know if that was a progression as they got

00:14:29.179 --> 00:14:33.940
more comfortable or if maybe that third lab, which had to do with the t-tests, was particularly

00:14:33.940 --> 00:14:38.619
helpful one way or the other. I like that that was positive and also that it improved

00:14:38.619 --> 00:14:43.260
over these three labs that I surveyed heavily on.

00:14:43.260 --> 00:14:46.979
I really like this one. I feel proud of the work I produced on the assignment, the assignment

00:14:46.979 --> 00:14:52.059
being the actual data analysis, not these exercises. And they feel very proud of it.

00:14:52.059 --> 00:14:56.140
Almost none of them feel unproud of it. And most of them were kind of excited. And it

00:14:56.140 --> 00:15:00.739
was fun during these exercises to watch them hit knit on their file and go, oh, my gosh,

00:15:00.739 --> 00:15:04.820
it worked. This is cool, you know, and explore this data. That was very rewarding for me

00:15:04.820 --> 00:15:08.659
anyway. I surveyed them pretty heavily on the skills

