same time, same number of students. Homework was pretty much identical. I didn't tweak

00:16:49.340 --> 00:16:53.739
it too much between winter and fall. And the lab material was the same, the same data

00:16:53.739 --> 00:16:59.979
sets and questions, but it was split for the fall into this pre-lab and lab format.

00:16:59.979 --> 00:17:03.340
And so I asked them two questions. Halfway through the quarter, I asked them how much

00:17:03.340 --> 00:17:06.900
the homework assignments helped and how much the lab assignments helped. And what we found

00:17:06.900 --> 00:17:11.699
was not a huge change in the homework from winter to fall, which you would expect. It's

00:17:11.699 --> 00:17:15.939
the same homework. But the lab assignments, if you see here, I don't know why I keep forgetting

00:17:15.939 --> 00:17:22.500
this exists. There's lab assignments here. In the winter, like three-fourths of my class

00:17:22.500 --> 00:17:27.140
hated them or didn't think they were useful. And in the fall, most of the class did think

00:17:27.140 --> 00:17:30.459
they were useful or at least felt neutral. So I think that is maybe attributable to these

00:17:30.459 --> 00:17:33.180
exercises.

00:17:33.180 --> 00:17:36.859
So just some take-home messages, what worked well. I like that the students could analyze

00:17:36.859 --> 00:17:41.979
data from scratch themselves. Anecdotally, I really think the students ended up better

00:17:41.979 --> 00:17:47.739
off in the fall class. I like seeing them get excited about results.

00:17:47.739 --> 00:17:52.420
What didn't work? Well, first of all, these exercises, we banged them out. We are not

00:17:52.420 --> 00:17:56.540
developers. We're trying to be. We're getting there. But we're not. I'm going to hang myself

00:17:56.540 --> 00:18:00.699
out to dry again. This is kind of what it looks like when I have to input to output

00:18:00.699 --> 00:18:06.420
both the strings of code and also evaluate that code. In particular, I'm just going to

00:18:06.420 --> 00:18:11.579
really hang myself out to dry. A lot of people I know will get mad at me for that. EvalParse.

00:18:12.060 --> 00:18:15.060
I know it's a crime. But I don't know what else to do. And I wanted to do something.

00:18:15.060 --> 00:18:20.979
And something is better than nothing. So there we are. Sorry, Dave Robinson.

00:18:20.979 --> 00:18:24.819
And so apart from that, and this is kind of why I'm sharing it with you. One reason is

00:18:24.819 --> 00:18:28.500
in the hopes that there's people out there who might want to help me make this more of

00:18:28.500 --> 00:18:32.880
a usable, shareable, manageable tool.

00:18:32.880 --> 00:18:37.439
I think this idea of thinking through code, students tended to type their variable names

00:18:37.439 --> 00:18:40.739
for the new data into the exercise, which, of course, wouldn't run. But then they would

00:18:40.739 --> 00:18:45.219
copy-paste, which isn't quite what I was hoping, but maybe it's okay. And motivating

00:18:45.219 --> 00:18:48.900
the students, they really were disturbed by the fact that they were spending class time

00:18:48.900 --> 00:18:51.579
on something that wasn't on the exam.

00:18:51.579 --> 00:18:55.260
So my advice for you, the growing pains are worth it. There is a headache, but it's worth

00:18:55.260 --> 00:19:00.219
it. I think if you have an idea for a teaching tool, build it. It's not perfect. Mine is

00:19:00.219 --> 00:19:06.800
ugly, but it's cool and it helped. And that these kids can handle R. They really can.

00:19:06.800 --> 00:19:10.540
They grew up with computers. They can do more than they think they can. They can think about

00:19:10.540 --> 00:19:16.900
data. They can do it. And so can the people teaching them. So I hope that more classes

00:19:16.900 --> 00:19:21.219
will really engage with coding instead of just applets in the future. That's my goal.

00:19:21.219 --> 00:19:26.180
All right. So the GitHub repository there has all the material for these exercises if

00:19:26.180 --> 00:19:31.619
you want to use or, better yet, edit them. Those three demos, the links are here. And

00:19:31.619 --> 00:19:35.219
then contact info for me or Hunter. And that's all I got.

00:19:35.780 --> 00:19:36.780
Thank you.

00:19:36.780 --> 00:19:44.780
We have time for one question.

00:19:44.780 --> 00:19:58.260
Hi. This is a great talk. Thank you very much. So a lot of times when I hear these discussions

00:19:58.260 --> 00:20:03.140
about sort of computing and statistics pedagogy, they're like kind of along two veins. One

00:20:03.140 --> 00:20:06.939
is I think kind of what you're doing here, which is using R and Shiny and these kinds

00:20:06.939 --> 00:20:14.300
of tools to improve the teaching of classical topics. And the other one is to kind of replace

00:20:14.300 --> 00:20:19.180
like the sort of teaching of classical topics with more computationally based stuff like

00:20:19.180 --> 00:20:23.979
permutation testing, bootstraps, stuff like that, right up front instead of normal derivations

00:20:23.979 --> 00:20:27.420
of t-tests, things like that. I was wondering if that sort of like second component of it

00:20:27.420 --> 00:20:32.420
is something like you and your colleagues have like discussed as like you're incorporating

00:20:32.420 --> 00:20:35.060
more of this stuff into these earlier classes.

00:20:35.060 --> 00:20:38.939
Yeah, totally. So I think the question is about like using computing just to reinforce

00:20:38.939 --> 00:20:43.459
things like t-tests versus to introduce things like permutation tests that get the spirit

00:20:43.459 --> 00:20:48.020
of hypothesis testing without the math maybe necessary. Yeah, that's a big discussion.

00:20:48.020 --> 00:20:52.660
I think Beth Chance teaches a class like fully on simulation permutation tests and none of

00:20:52.660 --> 00:20:56.060
the other stuff. For me, I kind of believe in teaching the classical concepts because

00:20:56.060 --> 00:21:00.300
they are going to see that. Even if they never do stat, they're going to read papers in their

00:21:00.339 --> 00:21:04.579
fields and it's probably going to have a T-score. They should know what that is. And so mostly

00:21:04.579 --> 00:21:10.540
I've been using it to reinforce those concepts, but also I do feel really strongly about don't

00:21:10.540 --> 00:21:15.140
do something in a class that is never ever going to happen in a real world. So as maybe

00:21:15.140 --> 00:21:22.140
those things go away, then it would make more sense to emphasize the other stuff.

